  mos mosfet          it prevents the electricity from following until it receives a signal 
                     imagine water following through a pipe, we can block the flow with a disc
                      there is a hole in one side of the disc and it is spring loaded.....
                      another pipe connects to this disc with enough pressure or voltage, we can move the disc, allowing the water to flow again (branch pipe)
                      the more pressure we apply, the more water can flow
                      thats what happening inside of a mosfet. there's a metal oxide (gate, drain, source) semiconductor inside
                      with enough pressure on the gate pin, a channel forms that allows electrons to flow from one side to the other.
                      two types of mosfet..
                      - enhancement type mosfet: if we apply pressure to make it work (broken line)
                      - depletion type mosfet:   if we apply pressure to stop the circuit (straight line)
                      this pressure can be negative or positive (N-Channel <G, P-Channel >R)
                        it can be confusing, so check the datasheet, using the number (the part number) on the front. otherwise it can be destroyed

